               <surname>Englefield</surname>
            </persName>
            <birth when="1752"/>
            <death when="1822"/>
            <note>Seventh baronet from 1780 and a prominent Roman Catholic antiquarian and geologist. FRSL.</note>
         </person>
         <person xml:id="person_125">
            <persName xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <forename type="first">James</forename>
               <surname>Hutton</surname>
            </persName>
            <birth when="1726"/>
            <death when="1797"/>
            <note>Scottish geologist, agriculturalist and chemical manufacturer. His Theory of the Earth (1795) is one of the foundations of modern geology. Davy discussed Hutton's theories in his lectures and visited some of the key geological sites that Hutton used in his work. </note>
         </person>
         <person xml:id="person_508">
            <persName xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <surname>Lucretius</surname>
            </persName>
            <birth when="99 BCE"/>
            <death when="c. 55 BCE"/>
            <note>Roman poet and philosopher. His only known work is the materialist philosophical poem De rerum natura.</note>
         </person>
         <person xml:id="person_922">
            <persName xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
               <forename type="first">Adair</forename>
               <surname>Crawford</surname>
            </persName>
            <birth when="1748"/>
            <death when="1795"/>
            <note> A British chemist, physician, and fellow of the Royal Society. He was a pioneer in the development of calorimetric methods for measuring the specific heat capacity of substances and the heat of chemical reactions.</note>
         </person>
         <person xml:id="person_321">
            <persName xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">
